=== THE RULER (seed-jitter range distribution — 'how much can a score move for NO reason') ===
split      n_cells     median       mean        p75        p90        max        min
Public          16    0.00588    0.00945    0.01451    0.01909    0.02570    0.00141
Private         16    0.00666    0.00881    0.01332    0.01815    0.02631    0.00244
BOTH            32    0.00615    0.00913                          0.02631    0.00141
  ^ Public and Private are reported SEPARATELY on purpose (round82's lesson: the two splits can move in opposite directions, so a ruler built on one is not a ruler for the other).

=== THE THREE NOISE SCALES (do not confuse them) ===
A past round's delta must be compared against the scale that matches the STATISTIC it reported, not against whichever number is most flattering.
Public: median per-dataset sigma          = 0.00188
Public: single-seed PAIRED-DELTA scale    = 0.00266  (= sqrt(2)*sigma; a per-dataset delta smaller than this is noise)
Public: MEAN-over-16-datasets delta scale = 0.00130  (= sqrt(2*sum sigma_i^2)/16; the headline stat past rounds reported; 2-sigma = 0.00261)
Private: median per-dataset sigma          = 0.00216
Private: single-seed PAIRED-DELTA scale    = 0.00306  (= sqrt(2)*sigma; a per-dataset delta smaller than this is noise)
Private: MEAN-over-16-datasets delta scale = 0.00126  (= sqrt(2*sum sigma_i^2)/16; the headline stat past rounds reported; 2-sigma = 0.00252)
  Note the mean-delta scale is ~4x tighter than the per-dataset scale (averaging 16 datasets averages the noise down by ~sqrt(16)). This is why a mean delta can be real even when every individual dataset's delta is inside its own noise band.

=== CALIBRATION (retroactive: which past-round delta magnitudes clear the noise?) ===
For each delta magnitude past rounds have argued over, the fraction of (dataset x split) cells whose OWN seed-jitter range already exceeds it. A per-dataset delta of size D on a dataset whose range > D is indistinguishable from reseeding luck.
  |delta|   cells with range > |delta|    verdict for a PER-DATASET delta
   0.0005   32/32 (100.0%)                       NOISE on most datasets
   0.0010   32/32 (100.0%)                       NOISE on most datasets
   0.0020   31/32 ( 96.9%)                       NOISE on most datasets
   0.0050   21/32 ( 65.6%)                       NOISE on most datasets

Same question for the MEAN-over-16-datasets delta:
  Public   mean delta  0.0005 =  0.38 sigma  -> BELOW 1-sigma — NOISE
  Public   mean delta  0.0010 =  0.77 sigma  -> BELOW 1-sigma — NOISE
  Public   mean delta  0.0020 =  1.53 sigma  -> 1-2 sigma — SUGGESTIVE, not conclusive
  Public   mean delta  0.0050 =  3.83 sigma  -> > 2-sigma — likely REAL
  Private  mean delta  0.0005 =  0.40 sigma  -> BELOW 1-sigma — NOISE
  Private  mean delta  0.0010 =  0.79 sigma  -> BELOW 1-sigma — NOISE
  Private  mean delta  0.0020 =  1.59 sigma  -> 1-2 sigma — SUGGESTIVE, not conclusive
  Private  mean delta  0.0050 =  3.97 sigma  -> > 2-sigma — likely REAL

=== IS THE SHIPPED 08 LUCKY? (where random_state=0 sits in its own seed distribution) ===
08 hardcodes random_state=0. If 0 were a cherry-picked lucky seed, its percentile would sit systematically above 50% and its mean z above 0. If 0 is just an arbitrary default (as the recipe's provenance suggests), the percentiles should scatter around 50% and mean z around 0.
split       mean pctile  median pctile    mean z   cells seed0 > own mean
Public            43.1%          38.9%     -0.09             7/16
Private           52.1%          50.0%     +0.05            10/16
  (Under 'seed 0 is arbitrary', mean pctile ~= 50%, mean z ~= 0, and seed0 beats its own mean on ~half the cells. A binomial sign test on 16 cells needs >=12/16 to reach p<0.05 two-sided.)
  Public: seed 0 is the BEST of the 10 seeds on 2 dataset(s) [train_11, train_16]; the WORST on 2 [train_08, train_12]
  Private: seed 0 is the BEST of the 10 seeds on 3 dataset(s) [train_07, train_11, train_16]; the WORST on 3 [train_04, train_12, train_15]

=== FLIPPER HYPOTHESIS (train_15: 'n=500, any perturbation moves it') ===
The hypothesis bundles TWO claims that the data separates. Claim 1 (WEAK): train_15 is jittery in absolute terms. Claim 2 (STRONG): train_15 is SPECIAL — the flipper, the one to watch. They are scored separately below.
Public: range=0.01429 (std=0.00432) -> rank 5/16 among the 16 datasets; 2.4x the median dataset's range (0.00588)
Private: range=0.01378 (std=0.00455) -> rank 4/16 among the 16 datasets; 2.1x the median dataset's range (0.00666)
(train_15: n=500, ratio=0.06000, n_obj=24, l2=1.0, msl=70)
CLAIM 1 (train_15 is jittery): SUPPORTED on both splits — its range is well above the median dataset's, so a delta reported on train_15 alone is weak evidence.
CLAIM 2 (train_15 is THE flipper / uniquely twitchy): NOT SUPPORTED — it is rank 5 (Public) / 4 (Private), behind train_05, train_16, train_13 and train_09. It is NOT the most seed-sensitive dataset on either split.
NET: the useful half of the hypothesis survives (don't trust small train_15 deltas), the headline half does not (train_15 is not special). Watching train_15 as THE canary is a mistake: it would miss train_05 and train_16, which are jitterier on both splits. See the next section for what actually drives jitter.

=== WHAT DRIVES JITTER (Spearman rank correlation of seed-range vs dataset properties) ===
If jitter tracked the 08 gates (ratio / msl / object columns), the gates would be implicated in it. If it tracks n, jitter is just small-sample instability and has nothing to do with the recipe's knobs.
property        rho vs Public range  rho vs Private range
n_train                      -0.720                -0.770
ratio                        +0.800                +0.806
n_obj                        -0.086                +0.001
msl                          +0.460                +0.467
l2                           +0.626                +0.658
  Read: a strongly NEGATIVE rho vs n_train means 'smaller datasets jitter more' — i.e. jitter is small-sample instability, NOT something the 08 gates cause. ratio/msl/l2 correlations are largely INDUCED by n (the gates key off ratio = n_feat/n, so they are entangled with n by construction) and should not be read as causal.

=== WORKED EXAMPLE — round82 re-judged with this ruler (payoff (a)) ===
round82 concluded the categorical mask 'earns its keep' because removing it (ORD) lost AUC. This ruler re-judges that headline:
  Public: ORD mean delta = -0.00070 vs mean-delta noise 0.00130 -> 0.54 sigma -> BELOW 1 sigma — NOISE, the headline does not survive
    per-dataset: only 1/16 of ORD's deltas exceed that dataset's OWN seed-range; the rest are inside jitter.
  Private: ORD mean delta = -0.00199 vs mean-delta noise 0.00126 -> 1.58 sigma -> 1-2 sigma — SUGGESTIVE only, not conclusive
    per-dataset: only 1/16 of ORD's deltas exceed that dataset's OWN seed-range; the rest are inside jitter.
  => round82's Public headline was 0.5 sigma (noise) and its Private headline ~1.6 sigma (suggestive). The direction it reported may well be right, but the evidence was weaker than it read. This is exactly the correction the ruler was built to supply.

=== SEED-AVERAGING (candidate A) — the direct evidence ===
Seed-averaging over K seeds suppresses exactly the sigma measured above, by roughly sqrt(K) (exactly sqrt(K) only if seeds were independent; prediction averaging is better-behaved than that, so this is a conservative floor). Expected residual jitter of a K-seed average:
split       K=1 (shipped)        K=3        K=5       K=10
Public            0.00188    0.00109    0.00084    0.00060
Private           0.00216    0.00125    0.00097    0.00068
  This does NOT say seed-averaging raises the mean AUC — it says it shrinks the variance of whatever AUC you land on. That is the mechanism by which candidate A (round29/69) would help, and it is now measured rather than assumed.

